o cut out the image of the apple. This was applied to the above sequence as an overlay, timing the apple fall to coincide with the actors reaction, the angle of the apple image and direction of movement was adjusted to try to make it more realistic. This final sequence was then processed with an 'old film' effect and adjusted to try to match it with the original footage.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Wake-up scene'''%0a%3c The original wake up scene (modern day) was removed and a new version filmed to match with the new introductory scene. In the original version this sequence takes place after the credits, but we noticed that it was unexpected and often resulted in the cinema lights coming up after the credits before hastily being dimmed again. Therefore we have moved this sequence to before the final credits.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''End Credits'''%0a%3c %0a%3c One thing that was always intended for the end-credits was that the actors names would change at the same time as their photos, from old-fashioned to modern. This was never included in the original version due to time constraints but has now been added.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''General Brightness/Contrast Issues'''%0a%3c %0a%3c The original film was filmed on two cameras. This resulted in some inconsistencies in brightness/contrast in different scenes. We have attempted to address this for some of the worst cases.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> Another area which we were never entirely happy with was the sequence where the giant apple falls from the tree, hitting our hero on the head. On the original shoot, this had been achieved by lowering the apple on a string, with the idea that the string would then be removed post-production. Even once the string was removed however this resulted in a particularly unrealistic effect as the apple appeared to defy gravity as it fell at variable speeds as it was lowered. We decided to use the original footage to re-edit this scene, using chromakey to superimpose the apple over the live footage. This was not without problems however, as the original apple had to somehow be removed from the footage. We were able to create a still image of the background of the scene using a section where the actor and apple were off-screen. Two frames were selected, with the string visible in both but in different positions. Using both these frames, we were able to construct a single background frame with no string visible.%0a
